            <h2>Introduction to Queues</h2>
            <p>A queue is a linear data structure that follows the First In, First Out (FIFO) principle. Elements are added at the rear and removed from the front, making queues ideal for scenarios where order matters, such as task scheduling and buffering.</p>
            
            <h2>Why Use Queues?</h2>
            <p>Queues are useful for:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Managing tasks in the order they arrive.</li>
                <li>Handling requests in a sequential manner.</li>
                <li>Implementing breadth-first search (BFS) algorithms.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h2>Common Operations</h2>
            <p>Common operations on queues include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Enqueuing elements to the rear.</li>
                <li>Dequeuing elements from the front.</li>
                <li>Peeking at the front element without removing it.</li>
                <li>Checking if the queue is empty.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
